      <hedline>
        <hl1>Of Two Minds on Social Security</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas P Solferino letter comments on June 20 editorial comparing Social Security and other retirement plans proposed by Vice Pres Al Gore and Gov George W Bush (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Safer Retirement Plan'' (editorial, June 20):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Safer Retirement Plan'' (editorial, June 20):</p>
        <p>Unlike Vice President Al Gore's Social Security plan, Gov. George W. Bush's plan addresses the problem where it lies, within the Social Security system. By giving future recipients the choice to invest part of their contribution into individual retirement accounts, Mr. Bush is putting the ''trust'' back into the system.</p>
        <p>Mr. Bush's plan creates no new tax or entitlement, and working people will know that their money is actually earning interest (or if invested in equities, adding value). The best way to shore up Social Security is to decrease future retirees' dependency on benefits without the threat of increased spending. In this regard, Mr. Bush's plan is superior.</p>
        <p>THOMAS P. SOLFERINO  Mineola, N.Y., June 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
